    "L6_top_supported_1": "If epistemic utility is defined by information content cont(g) in a\ntruth-dependent way, so that\n\n\\[\nU(g,e) =\n\\begin{cases}\ncont(g) \\text{ if } g \\text{ is true}\\\\\n-cont(\\neg g) \\text{ if } g \\text{ is false},\n\\end{cases}\n\\]\n\n(i,e., in accepting hypothesis \\(g\\), we gain the content of \\(g\\) if\n\\(g\\) is true, but we lose the content of the true hypothesis \\(\\neg\ng\\) if \\(g\\) is false), then the expected utility \\(U(g\\mid e)\\) is\nequal to\n\n\\[\\tag{4}\nP(g\\mid e) - P(g)\n\\]\n\nThis measure combines the criteria of boldness (small prior\nprobability \\(P(g))\\) and high posterior probability \\(P(g\\mid e)\\).",
    "L6_top_supported_2": "<!-- SEMANTIC INLINE LABELS START -->\n<details class=\"semantic-ai-inline-labels\">\n<summary><strong>Semantic Labels</strong> (click to show/hide)</summary>\n\nTotal tags: 16\n\n**Axiom (2)**\n- `Axiom` Science is progressive\n- `Axiom` Scientific knowledge is a process\n\n**Claim (10)**\n- `Claim` Acquisition and systematization of positive knowledge are cumulative -> parent: Science is progressive\n- `Claim` Scientific progress is questioned by philosophers -> parent: Science is progressive\n- `Claim` Different types of progress can be distinguished -> parent: Science is progressive\n- `Claim` Cognitive progress is distinct from other types of progress -> parent: Different types of progress can be distinguished\n- `Claim` Normative questions in philosophy of science can be reduced to historical investigations -> parent: Scientific progress is questioned by philosophers\n- `Claim` Scientific progress can lead to technological and social progress -> parent: Cognitive progress is distinct from other types of progress\n- `Claim` Philosophers have analyzed scientific change -> parent: Scientific knowledge is a process\n- `Claim` Scientific theories are evaluated based on empirical success -> parent: Scientific knowledge is a process\n- `Claim` Progress in science is linked to the problem-solving capacity of theories -> parent: Scientific theories evolve through problem-solving\n- `Claim` Scientific progress involves increasing understanding -> parent: Scientific knowledge is a process\n\n**Relationship (2)**\n- `Relationship` Cumulative view of scientific progress influences societal progress\n- `Relationship` Scientific theories evolve through problem-solving\n\n**secondary (1)**\n- `secondary` Historical examples of scientific change\n\n**primary (1)**\n- `primary` Quantitative studies on scientific publications\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- SEMANTIC INLINE LABELS END -->\n\n---",
    "L6_top_risky_1": "Convergence to the truth seems to be\nimpossible, if ontologies change with theories.",
